head: tẻoqdūe
body: ▯ is the answer to ▯, where the second blank necessarily refers to whatever question you just asked me."tẻoqdūe" is a technically logical answer to any question whatsoever. questioner: "Why do you beat your dog?" Answerer who doesn't feel like explaining that they never did beat their dog so the question is irrelevant and answers: "tẻoqdūe." Technically this counts, by definition, as an answer to the questioner's question, and may signal the answerer does not feel the need to give a more detailed answer. "Why are you such a dork?" "tẻoqdūe."

head: Tủqcā
body: ▯ is the ultimate explanation for everything in set ▯. (Defaults to the ultimate cause of the universe in context.) "Why didn't you do the laundry?" "Tủqcā" (could be translated as "The physical laws plus boundary conditions of the universe." "Tủqcā" is technically an answer to pretty much any question, and a signal that perhaps you should specify what level of explanation you are looking for before asking, like "what did you do this morning instead of the laundry" instead. Can also probably be used in physics contexts.

head: meq
body: quantifier: the proposition in which this quantifier appears is treated as a property with a lambda slot placed exactly where this quantifier appears; the resulting property is then claimed to satisfy the first slot of the predicate introduced by this quantifier.

notes.content: ``mủıdūa meq nỏa ní`` = ``nỏa mûıdūa ja ní``.

``meq hảo`` is similar to ``hão`` but instead of delivering a proposition (lû) to the first slot of ``hao`` as is the case with the latter, it passes a property (lî) to it. Compare ``chỏq jí ní jẽaq dảqfāı`` —"I use this increasingly frequently"— with ``chỏq meq pủıjēaq ní`` —"increasingly many ones use this"—.

What can be expressed as ``gủaı meq dùq póq`` under the alternative definition #46CV57Aje can be expressed as per this very definition as ``gủaı póq ru meq hỏpā dủq``, which is three syllables more. Hopefully the additional flexibility allowed by this one definition is a sufficient compensation.

head: oı

Extreme doubt illocution. Means "it is said that", "im just throwing out there that", or "hypothetically". Presents text as interesting important rather than true. Can also be used for sarcasm, works like a Toan '/s'.

gỉ ní dảısīo bảkāmōqdā oı = "'this' 'illocution' 'is' 'a' 'good' 'idea.'"(these are scare quotes. intended to illustrate doubt. Sentences marked with oı will lack the connotation of being immensely annoying, hopefully)

head: zoı
body:
Particle: the following word renders the containing predicate false, but replace it with another word that is thought of by the user of zoi and it becomes true. May be used for sarcasm.

ex. zoı gỉ ní da = this is "good"(true sentence, sarcastic)
      gỉ ní da = this is good(false sentence)
      hủı ní da = this is bad(true if huı is what the zoı-er is trying to imply by zoı)

head: kuxāı
body: 'orientation'; ▯ʼs orientation in aspect/relevant to property ▯  is described by property ▯

notes.content: Word form inspired by "kuaı". The second place relates to a scale and/or collection of beliefs or behaviors and the third place describes exactly what behaviors or beliefs the referent of the first place exhibits, or where they are on the scale

"Kủxāı súq lî củe ru cảq ja baq jủaocīao hı moq?"—"What is your political orientation" (Or "Please describe what properties best describe your beliefs/behaviors as relevant to ruling and managing societies")
This bisyllabic root is purposefully very broad and as such can be used to name sexual, gender, political, etc. orientation
This could be used for a "secret society" which can be microsocieties of their own, but is normally used for any governed subsection of human civilization that more or less shares a common culture
